Cold is the new cool
•
I am a firm believer that the BEST time to photograph Minnesota’s North Shore is when it’s the coldest. The snow and ice formations are nothing short of breathtaking!
•
I’m heading up to shoot photos on the North Shore at the end of December and am looking for ideas for new places that I should check out. What are some of your favorite places to photograph, hike, and spend time when it gets cold out?

Waves roll into the shoreline below Split Rock Lighthouse on the 47th anniversary of the sinking of the Edmund Fitzgerald on November 10, 2022.
•
The gales of November were out in full force on Lake Superior with 55mph wind gusts 11+’ waves!
•
I took a 450 mile road trip up to the North Shore to capture the massive waves and the lighting of Split Rock Lighthouse. I finished off the day with 2000+ photos taken and a good case of wind burn on my face from being out in the elements all day capturing Lake Superior’s raging beauty.
•
All throughout the day I couldn’t help but think of the 29 crew members who lost their lives 47 years ago on the Edmund Fitzgerald in weather a lot like this day had.

•
I took this flight with two friends, @levikj who piloted, and @vincentledvina. We spent a bit over three hours in the plane on our flight from Fairbanks to Denali and back.
•
As we were circling Denali, the wildest aspect to me was looking out the window while at our max altitude and looking up to see the mountain towering still thousands of feet above our heads.

Frigid Beauty
•
The morning I captured this photo in Duluth it felt like -45°f and the ice formations were putting on a beautiful display at sunrise. I walked up and down the Park Point beach to find the perfect ice formation to photograph. This tall shard caught my eye due to its luminescence with the Sun hitting the top of the shard and watching the light dissipate as it traveled down the ice.
•
I had some fun capturing this photo as well in a technical standpoint because I used a tilt shift lens to capture a massive bracketed HDR panorama of the scene so I could capture as much detail possible. For example, the original file size is 115 megapixels, and printed at its native size would be 30x40”, but could easily be printed larger!
•

Remembering the anniversary of most exciting night of photography in my life, March 20th, 2021. (1/3)
•
I started out the night by driving to Split Rock Lighthouse from my office in Minneapolis. There I met up with @splitrockkeeperhayes and @nicholas_j._narog_photography. We started out our night of photography on the beach at Split Rock Lighthouse waiting on potential Northern Lights show. Nothing at that point was occurring, so we decided to take a quick drive up the North Shore to Palisade Head. 
•
Once we arrived to the lower parking lot of Palisade Head, we had to hike up the snowy and icy road to the cliffs looking north. Soon after we made it to the edge of the cliffs, the aurora began to pop off and light up the entire sky. We could hear people up and down the cliffs cheering and yelling with joy and excitement as the sky began to shine bright with green and red pillars of aurora.
• 
While we were on the cliffs of Palisade Head, I met and struck up a conversation with @vincentledvina, and we nerded out about the aurora and photography for hours. This conversation has ultimately led to a friendship with Vincent and has brought me up to Alaska, where he lives, to photograph the aurora with him.
•
As the skies were still alive with aurora, we decided to drive back to Split Rock Lighthouse to capture the aurora overhead and the rising Milky Way core over the lighthouse. Hayes, Nicholas, and I had the beach all to ourselves and we watched the aurora dance overhead and sat in the calm, but exciting, moment together thinking how lucky we were to be able to experience what I consider the most exciting night of photography I have ever had in my life.

An aerial view of Split Rock Lighthouse and its accompanying historical buildings.
•
In the background behind the lighthouse you can see Gold Rock Point and the final resting place of the shipwreck of the Madeira. “The Madeira was an unpowered schooner-barge normally towed behind a steamship, a common practice that cut the cost of transporting bulk cargoes of iron ore, lumber and grain. Another victim of the infamous storm of November 1905, she sank on November 28 around 3 am. After drifting from the William Edenborn, the helpless Madeira crashed into the shores of Gold Rock and began breaking up. As a result of Seaman Fred Benson's heroic acts, all but one member of the crew were saved. This shipwreck is historically significant as the best and one of the few known surviving examples of a schooner-barge. Though it did break into numerous pieces, the major diagnostic elements of the hull are relatively intact.” - MNHS.org
•
Further in the distance is Silver Bay, Palisade Head, and Tettegouche State Park.

An aerial view of Split Rock Lighthouse and its accompanying historical buildings.
•
In the background behind the lighthouse you can see Gold Rock Point and the final resting place of the shipwreck of the Madeira. “The Madeira was an unpowered schooner-barge normally towed behind a steamship, a common practice that cut the cost of transporting bulk cargoes of iron ore, lumber and grain. Another victim of the infamous storm of November 1905, she sank on November 28 around 3 am. After drifting from the William Edenborn, the helpless Madeira crashed into the shores of Gold Rock and began breaking up. As a result of Seaman Fred Benson's heroic acts, all but one member of the crew were saved. This shipwreck is historically significant as the best and one of the few known surviving examples of a schooner-barge. Though it did break into numerous pieces, the major diagnostic elements of the hull are relatively intact.” - MNHS.org
•
Further in the distance is Silver Bay, Palisade Head, and Tettegouche State Park.

Split Rock Lighthouse will be lit tonight from 9-11pm to celebrate the legacy of Gordon Lightfoot, singer of the 1976 hit song “The Wreck of the Edmund Fitzgerald.”
•
“We mourn the passing and celebrate the legacy of folk singer Gordon Lightfoot, who died on May 1 at the age of 84. Although not a native Minnesotan, his 1976 hit song "The Wreck of the Edmund Fitzgerald" is indelibly tied to Minnesota's North Shore of Lake Superior, and particularly to Split Rock Lighthouse, which commemorates the Fitzgerald and honors her 29 crew members and all the sailors lost on the Great Lakes with a beacon lighting and event on the anniversary of the sinking each year.
•
To honor Lightfoot's legacy, Split Rock Lighthouse will have a special lighting tonight, May 3, from 9-11 pm. The historic site and visitor center will be closed. Visitors can park at the adjacent state park to see the light (a State Park sticker or day pass is required.)”- Split Rock Lighthouse

Northern Lights over Split Rock Lighthouse!
•
Unfortunately the reports of Northern Lights over the next couple of nights were falsely reported by news stations nationwide searching for likes, comments, and views, ultimately making them more money by taking advantage of people with hopes of seeing the aurora.
•
The aurora can only be predicted with some confidence about three days prior to an event, and even then, things can be incorrect.
•
Please do not let these false reports discourage you from chasing the northern lights in the future! The Sun is coming up on a solar maximum, with more chances ultimately coming from that!
•
Experiencing the aurora is truly a life changing experience and is well worth the wait to see.

Kayaking over the Madeira shipwreck
•
This has been a bucket list shot of mine for years, and I am glad to have finally made it happen!
•
The Madeira was sunk and destroyed during the worst storm in recorded history on Lake Superior on November 28, 1905.
•
In this photo, you can see the bow section under the left buoy, a bit of the stern section under the right buoy, and a large chunk of the ship off to the right side of Gold Rock Point. While my wife and I were out on our kayak, we also found large chunks of metal from the Madeira washed up along the rocky shoreline from 1905.
•
To give some sense of size of this scene, the kayak is 14’ in length. The Madeira was 436’ in length. The wreck spans the area all around Gold Rock Point and is in a depth of 15-100’ under the surface.
•
Disclaimer: to capture this photo, my drone flight was launched, operated, and landed outside of Minnesota State Park and Minnesota Historical Society property

The annular eclipse over a lone spire in Utah
•
I am extremely proud of this photo for a multitude of reasons. I was told about this location a couple of months ago and when I found out that it was in the path of the annular eclipse I began doing an insane amount of research on the location to make this photo happen. To ensure that I was able to capture the eclipse directly over the spire I had to find the exact location of the tip of the spire, how high it is off the ground, the millimeter lens that I would be using, and various other factors. With that data in hand I was able to precisely pinpoint exactly where I needed to setup a camera to capture the eclipse precisely over the spire. Needless to say I obsessed about this photo so much that I lost a lot of sleep over it and even dreamt of the day of the photo well before it even happened.

Seeing this lone spire in the middle of the desert is like something straight out of a Star Wars movie. From the bottom of the floor to the tip of the point, it stands roughly 140’ in height and is a wildly impressive structure.

The foreground image was captured a day prior to the recent annular solar eclipse during a location scouting mission and the Milky Way captured the next night at the same latitude. A band of aurora and star trails over the northern Minnesota wilderness lit by the full Moon.
•
Captured at 1:45am on 12/1/23.
•
This night out chasing the aurora is the epitome of the saying, “you win some, you lose some.” I drove up to the North Shore after my work day in hopes of capturing the extremely strong aurora that was predicted. The night started off with a CME hit around 6:30pm, which helped create a band of aurora on the horizon. The group of photographers that I was with ended up at various locations along the shore and inland trying to find good views looking north, all while waiting for the stronger CME to hit Earth and cause the predicted aurora that would span the entire expanse of the sky. I ultimately finished off the night at Split Rock Lighthouse, and left there around 4:30am when current conditions were not favorable due to clouds covering the sky. I also had to take off to make it back to the cities for work. About an hour after I left, I saw reports that the entire sky lit up red with the effects from the next strong CME that hit the Earth.
•
Sometimes you can’t get all the shots that you want, and it’s not fun staying up all night and driving 600+ miles to miss the big show. Through it all, what I am thankful for out of everything is the great group of guys who I was able to spend time with that night along the North Shore.
•
It’s also good knowing that there will be countless more times coming up to chase aurora with the Sun approaching its solar maximum.

My top moments of 2023!
•
2023 was an incredible year for photography and here are my top ten favorite moments organized by date taken
•
1. Aurora in Alaska selfie. Fairbanks, Alaska (1/22/23)
2. Flying to Denali from Fairbanks, Alaska (1/22/23)
3. Inside Castner Glacier. Delta Junction, Alaska (1/23/23)
4. An aerial view of Split Rock Lighthouse from a drone. Piloted from a tandem kayak on Lake Superior. Two Harbors, Minnesota (7/23/23)
5. Split Rock Lighthouse illuminated for the anniversary lighting of the first lighting. Captured from Day Hill. Two Harbors, Minnesota (7/31/23)
6. Vibrant fall colors in northern Minnesota seen from the air. Lutsen, Minnesota (9/17/23)
7. Delicate Arch in Arches National Park at sunset. Moab, Utah (10/12/23)
8. The annular solar eclipse over a volcanic rock spire in the desert. Hanksville, Utah (10/14/23)
9. Fall colors in Minneapolis seen from the air. Minneapolis, Minnesota (10/23/23)
10. Massive Lake Superior waves pound the Tettegouche State Park shoreline. Silver Bay, Minnesota (12/26/23)
•
I also wanted to say a MASSIVE thank you for your support this year! 2023 was a huge year for engagement on my content on my Facebook and Instagram pages with 400,000 shares, 1 million likes, 11 million people reached, and 21 million impressions! 
•
Thank you for your continued support!

Minneapolis Lights
•
This view from the 24th St footbridge is a favorite of mine of Minneapolis, but can be extremely challenging to capture all the details in the scene. To ensure that I kept all the details in the highlights of the bright lights of the vehicles passing under the bridge and the skyline in the background as well as the dark shadows, I captured 45 photos with shutter speeds ranging from 1/8” to 30”. This would give me the most latitude to create the final image, and much closer match what the human eye can see.
•
I hope you enjoy the photo, and the extra efforts I put in to capture and edit the photo!
